dances.description:
*Bolero* is unique among competitive American Rhythm dances in that it requires not only cuban motion, but contra body movement as found in the smooth dances and rise and fall as is found in the [waltz].   For the purpose of music4dance categorization Bolero is the slowest of the three competition dances that are danced to *Rumba* style music, the other two being the Rumbas from the [International Latin] and [American Rhythm] categories.

The Bolero is generally danced as the fourth dance of [American Rhythm five dance] competitions.
dances.name: Bolero

dances.description: Bossa Nova is a Brazilian dance related to the *Brazilian Samba*, but danced to the slower beat of Bossa Nova music. It is characterized by a slow swaying motion of the hips.
dances.name: Bossa Nova

dances.description:
The *Cha Cha* is danced to the music of the same name introduced by Cuban composer and violinist Enrique Jordin in 1953. This rhythm was developed from the danzon by a syncopation of the fourth beat. The Cha Cha is danced in 4/4 time and the fourth beat is split in two.  This give the cha cha both its characteristic rhythm (2, 3,4 & 1) and its onomatopoeic name (two  three Cha Cha one).

The *Cha Cha* is generally danced as the first dance of [American Rhythm] and second dance of the [International Latin] five dance competitions.
dances.name: Cha Cha

dances.description:
The *Mambo* is a fusion of Swing and Cuban music developed from Danzon and was heavily influenced by the Jazz musicians of the 1930s.  The competition dance was influenced by the Cuban music and style, but is formalized nearly beyond recognition.  It is characterized by breaking on the 2 in 4/4 time and a compact basic movement.

The *Mambo* is generally danced as the fifth and final  dance of [American Rhythm five dance] competitions.
dances.name: Mambo

dances.description:
There are two competition ballroom dances called *Rumba*.  One in the [International Latin] round that based on what the Cubans called bolero-son and is danced in a similar pattern to the American Style [Bolero] and the other in the [American Rhythm] round which is danced to a faster beat and takes a box step as its basic figure.  

The American Style Bolero (96-104 BPM), the International Rumba (100-108 BPM), and the American Rumba (120-144 BPM) are all in a subfamily of Latin dance that are danced to similar music at a range of tempi.

The *Rhumba* is generally danced as the second dance of [American Rhythm] and third dance of [International Latin] five dance competitions.
dances.name: Rumba

dances.description:
*Paso Doble* or pasodoble is a lively style of dance  to the duple meter march-like pasodoble music typically played in bullfights during the bullfighters' entrance to the ring or during the passes just before the kill.  In the ballroom dance the man plays the part of the bullfighter while the woman alternates between the role of the cape and that of the bull.

The *Paso Doble* is generally danced as the fourth dance of the [International Latin five dance] competitions.
dances.name: Paso Doble

dances.description:
The *Samba* is a lively, rhythmical dance of Brazilian origin in 2/4 time danced to Samba music.  It is characterized by slight downward bouncing or dropping action and rotating line of dance figures.

The Samba is generally danced as the first dance of the [International Latin five dance] competitions.
dances.name: Samba

dances.description: *Salsa* is danced to music of the [same name](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salsa_music).  It is a club dance with many variations including New York, LA, Afro-Latin, Columbian and Cuban.  Salsa is most closely related to [Mambo] and [Cha cha] of the [competition ballroom dances](https://www.music4dance.net/dances/ballroom-competition-categories).
dances.name: Salsa

dances.description: *Bachata* is a family of dances all of which are traditionally danced to [Bachata Music](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bachata_(music)) of the Dominican Republic.  Styles of Bachata dance include *Authentic*or *Dominican Bachata*, *Western "traditional" Bachata*, *Bachata Moderna* and *Bachata Sensual*.  Bachata is related to Cuban style [Bolero] as well as [Rumba] and [Cha Cha].
dances.name: Bachata

dances.description:
Cumbia is both a style of dance and a style of music originating in the Columbian Caribbean coastal town of San Basilio.  Styles of Cumbia music include  Cumbia Sonidera, Cumbia Pegassera, and Cumbia Villera.
Cumbia is related to [Salsa] and [Samba].
dances.name: Cumbia

dances.description: *Balboa* is an early member of the [Swing] dance family that originated in southern California.  It is a close hold dance and while it can be danced to many tempos, for the purpose of our catalog we will be using the faster end of the *Balboa* range for categorization (40-65 measures per minute).
dances.name: Balboa

dances.description: The *Collegiate Shag* (or "Shag") is danced to up-tempo swing and pre-[swing music]. It is one of the early members of the  [swing] family of dances, tracing its roots back to the 1920s and 30s.
dances.name: Collegiate Shag

dances.description: The *Carolina Shag* is a style of [swing dance] that began in Myrtle Beach, South Carolina in the 40 and 50's.  It is danced to [Rhythm and Blues](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BRhythm+and+Blues:Music) or *Beach Music* in 4/4 time at a tempo of 27 to 33 measures per minute.
dances.name: Carolina Shag

dances.description:
The *Charleston* is a dance named for the harbor city of Charleston, South Carolina.  It was danced first as a solo dance and then as a partner dance in the 1920's and was one of the roots of [Lindy Hop] and therefore [Swing] dances in general.  Elements of the Charleston were also pulled into early [Foxtrot] dancing to create the [Quickstep] variation of the Foxtrot.

The Charleston beat is considered a clave rhythm and was popularized by the song called "The Charleston" from the Musical *Runnin' Wild* by composer James P. Johnson.  Charleston is danced with an eight beat basic to 4/4 time at 200-300 beats per minute.
dances.name: Charleston

dances.description:
*East Coast Swing* is a standardized dance in [American Rhythm] style competition dancing as well as a social partner dance.  It is one of a number of different swing dances that developed concurrently with the swing style of jazz music in the mid twentieth century.  This group of dances also includes [Lindy Hop],  [Carolina Shag], [Balboa], [West Coast Swing], and [Jive].  

This dance may also be referred to as Eastern Swing, Triple Swing, Triple Step Swing, American Swing, or just Swing.

The *East Coast Swing* is generally danced as the first dance of [American Rhythm] competitions.
dances.name: East Coast Swing

dances.description:
*The Hustle* is a member of the [swing] family of dances developed in the 1970's and is traditionally danced to [disco music](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BDisco:Music).

There is also a line dance called "The Hustle" danced to the  Van McCoy and the Soul City Symphony's [song](https://www.music4dance.net/song/details/91112c4b-32b1-4b6e-acf6-47aee94d1dfc) of the same name.

The partner dance developed in the US is also referred to as "New York Hustle", "LA Hustle" or "Latin hustle."  The "Detroit Hustle" is a slightly different dance, but it is generally danced to the same music.

In Europe there is a family of dances variously called DiscoFox, Disco Hustle, Swing Fox, Disco Swing, and Rock Fox. Although the moves are somewhat different, for the purposed of finding music to dance to these are close enough to be grouped in the same category as the US versions of the Hustle.
dances.name: Hustle

dances.description:
*Jive* is a standardized dance in [International Latin] Ballroom Dancing.  It is one of a number of different swing dances that developed concurrently with the Swing style of jazz music in the mid twentieth century.  This group of dances also includes [Lindy Hop], [Carolina Shag], [Balboa], [West Coast Swing], and [East Coast Swing].

The *Jive* is generally danced as the fifth and final dance of the [International Latin five dance] competitions.
dances.name: Jive

dances.description:
*Jump Swing* is one of most recent as well as one of the fastest of the [swing] family of dances.  It developed in southern California as part of the late 1990's [swing revival](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swing_revival) and is traditionally danced to jump blues, big band swing, and even rock.

*Jump Swing* is also called "Neo-swing" and "Retro Swing".
dances.name: Jump Swing

dances.description:
West Coast Swing is a member of the [swing] family of dances that developed in California in the 1930's.  It is characterized by the slow or down and dirty feel combined with and in the slot style and elastic connection.  This is one of the slower swing dances, danced to 4/4 music in the 28 to 32 measure per minute range.

West Coast Swing has also been called Western Swing, The New Yorker and California Swing.
dances.name: West Coast Swing

dances.description:
Lindy hop is the first of the family of swing dances, developing in Harlem in the 1920s and 1930s along with swing music, the popular style of jazz music at the time.  It evolved as a fusion of a number of dances that were popular at the time including Charleston, breakaway, and tap.

Lindy Hop has also been called Jitterbug and Swing.
dances.name: Lindy Hop

dances.description: Here at music4dance.net we're busily cataloging music with a specific interest in what dance styles 'work' with the music.  Since we come from a partner dancing background our system is set up primarily to work with traditional ballroom and partner social dancing like Swing, Salsa and Tango all of which are danced to music of a specific meter and tempo.  But with the interest in shows like *So You Think You Can Dance* and *Dancing With the Stars*, styles like Broadway, Contemporary, Jazz and even Ballet and Tap have started to show up in our database.  None of these style of dance operate under the same meter and tempo constraints that we are using, so we're creating initial place-holders for those styles and others that we'll roughly call 'performace' dances while we figure out how to generalize our website for such dance styles.

dances.name: Tap

dances.description:
*Ballroom Tango* is a dance descended from the dances of the same name in the Rio de la Plata region of South America.  It danced in 4/4 time and is characterized staccato movements and head snaps.   

[Tango] is generally danced second in [American Smooth four dance] and [International Standard five dance] competitions and while these two dance styles are closely related they are definitely distinct styles.
dances.name: Tango (Ballroom)

dances.description:
Argentine Tango often refers to the "Tango Trinity" or all "Three Faces of Tango":  The Tango, The [Milonga] and the [Tango Vals].  These dances evolved at the end of the nineteenth century in Buenos Aires and Montevideo and are danced to [Tango Music].

For the purpose of music4dance, we're using the category of Argentine Tango for what Argentine Tango dancers call just "Tango."  It is a dance performed in a close embrace to traditional Tango music in 2/4 or 4/4 time.

Like many dance styles, there is plenty of debate as to what to include an exclude in a category.  For our purposes, we're including most of what has over the years been termed Nuevo Tango music but placing [Neo Tango] in its own category.  However, any registered user can register their own opinion or refine the system by using the [tag editing](https://www.music4dance.net/blog/music4dance-help/tag-editing/) system.
dances.name: Argentine Tango

dances.description:
Neo-Tango is a relatively recent evolution of the [Tango] family.  Like its cousin the [Tango (Ballroom)], it is a result of migration north and evolving outside of Argentina.  Unlike Ballroom Tango, Neo-Tango's birth is placed about the year 2000.  For our purposes, Neo-Tango includes all of the modern Tango Fusion variations like electrotango and alternative tango.

While we haven't systematically added sub-categories to these dances, any registered user is welcome to use the [tag editor](https://www.music4dance.net/blog/music4dance-help/tag-editing/) to overlay their own sub-categories of Tango on the Neo-Tango [dance tag](https://www.music4dance.net/blog/music4dance-help/tag-definitions/).
dances.name: Neo Tango

dances.description: The Milonga or Tango Milonguero is faster than the [Argentine Tango] and danced with much smaller steps.  It is characteristically quick and sharp with less complicated movements and sequence than other [Tango] variations
dances.name: Milonga

dances.description: Tango Vals is one of the three aspects of traditional Argentine Tango.  It is distinct from the others in that it is danced to a 3/4 rhythm and in a generally circular movement.
dances.name: Tango Vals

dances.description: *Blues Dancing* is the family of dances that developed alongside of and were danced to [blues music](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BBlues:Music).  Contemporary blues dancing emerged as an offshoot of the 1980's swing revival and as such is an example of dance traditions coming full circle, as *blues dancing* was one of the parents of [swing dancing].
dances.name: Blues

dances.description: *Country Two Step* is a family of country/western dances usually danced to [country music](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BCountry:Music).  They are progressive dances like the waltz or foxtrot.  *Country Two Step* is also known as *country/western two-step*, *Texas two-step* or just *two-step*.
dances.name: Country Two Step

dances.description: *Motown* dance combines close partnering similar to [Blues Dance] with passes and turns in a [West Coast Swing] style.  All, of course, dance to the music of the [same name](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BMotown:Music).
dances.name: Motown

dances.description: *Night Club Two Step* was created by Buddy Schwimmer in the mid-1960s.  It is frequently dance to [soft rock ballads](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BSoft+Rock:Music) that have quick-quick-slow beat.  This dance is particularly suited to nightclub or [wedding music](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BWedding:Other) and is often used to enhance the basic [slow dance](https://www.music4dance.net/dances/castle-foxtrot). *Nightclub Two Step* is also known as the *disco two step* or the *California two step*.
dances.name: Night Club Two Step

dances.description: *The Polka* is a dance in 2/4 time originating in Bohemia (now part of the Czech Republic) in the middle of the 19th century.
dances.name: Polka

dances.description:
[Vernon and Irene Castle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vernon_and_Irene_Castle) were early ballroom dancers who were strongly associated with the [Foxtrot].  The [Foxtrot] evolved over time and the modern variations danced in a ballroom settings range from a medium tempo ([Slow Foxtrot]) to very fast ([Quickstep]).  

At music4dance our use of the term *Castle Foxtrot* as a proxy for Foxtrot-like dances that are danced more slowly even than the [Slow Foxtrot].  This is particularly interesting in the context of [first dances](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BFirst+Dance:Other) at weddings which are often danced to songs in this tempo range and called generically *Slow Dance*.  

If you're looking for music to *Slow Dance* to for your [first](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BFirst+Dance:Other), [mother/son](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BMother+Son:Other) or [father/daughter](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BFather+Daughter:Other) dance at your wedding, our list of Castle Foxtrot [wedding songs](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BWedding:Other&filter=Index-CFT-Dances) is a good place to start.
dances.name: Castle Foxtrot

dances.description:
The *Foxtrot* or *Slow Foxtrot* is characterized by long continuous flowing movements across the dance floor and is customarily danced to the same big band music as swing.  In the ballroom this dance is generally referred to as *Foxtrot* but here at music4dance, we are going to consistently use the modifier *Slow* to distinguish this dance from other dances in the [Foxtrot] family, such as the [Quickstep] and the [Castle Foxtrot] as well as allowing us to use the term [Foxtrot] to cover the entire family.

*Slow Foxtrot* is generally danced third in [American Smooth four dance] and fourth in [International Standard five dance] competitions.
dances.name: Slow Foxtrot

dances.description:
The *Quickstep* or  evolved from in the 1920s from a combination of [Slow Foxtrot], The Chase G Chug, Charleston, Shag, [Peabody], and One-Step.  While it evolved from the [Slow Foxtrot], the Quickstep now is quite separate.  It is characterized by high-energy and a exhilarating sense of flight and gliding.

The *Quickstep* is generally danced as the fifth and final dance in [International Standard five dance] competitions.
dances.name: QuickStep

dances.description: *The Peabody* is a one-step that is often danced to [Ragtime](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BRagtime:Music) or [Dixieland](https://www.music4dance.net/song/addtags?tags=%2BDixieland:Music) music.  It is a member of the [Foxtrot] family of dances and was once danced competitively in the [American Smooth] category of dances.
dances.name: Peabody

dances.description: The *Cross-step waltz*, or *Valse Boston* is a danced socially to [Waltz music] of a tempo between that of a [Slow Waltz] and [Viennese Waltz].
dances.name: Cross-step Waltz

dances.description:
The Slow Waltz is a dance in 3/4 time and is characterized by its graceful rise and fall motion.  It is danced primarily in closed position to the music of the same name.  At music4dance, we're be consistently referring to this dance as the *Slow Waltz* to distinguish it from the [Viennese Waltz] and other dances in the [Waltz] family, but in the context of ballroom dancing when the term *Waltz* is used by itself, this is generally the dance that is being referenced.

The Slow Waltz is generally danced first in both the [American Smooth] and [International Standard] dance competitions.
dances.name: Slow Waltz

dances.description:
The *Viennese Waltz* is original style of [Waltz].  As with all waltzes it is danced in 3/4 time to music of the same name.  It is the first ballroom dance to be performed in the closed hold or "waltz" position and is distinguished from other *Waltzes* in that it is danced to a fast tempo and is strongly characterized by circular motion of the partners rotating around each other as they progress down line of dance.

*Viennese Waltz* is generally danced as the fourth and final dance in [American Smooth four dance] and third in [International Standard five dance] competitions.
dances.name: Viennese Waltz

groups.name: Latin
groups.description:
In competitive ballroom dance the term Latin has a very specific meaning as the five dances that are danced as [International Latin] Five Dance round. This round consists of [Cha Cha], [Samba], [Rumba], [Paso Doble] and [Jive].    

Since our main purpose is match music to styles of dance, this isn't a particularly useful categorization. Instead, we are broadly grouping the dance styles that derive from Spain and Latin America as Latin. This gives a useful spectrum of tempos of similarly styled music that can be mapped to the various *Latin* dances. Note that we've pulled out the [Tango]s into their own category as there enough different styles of Tango each danced to similar music at slightly different tempi that they create a cohesive unit. There is some argument that the same should be done for other sub-groups of *Latin* dances and music.  For instance [Bolero], International [Rumba] and American Rumba create a spectrum of  tempi from about 25 to 36 measures per minute all danced to a similar style music. And [Samba] and [Bossa Nova] create a natural subcategory of Brazilian music with a similar feel at different tempi.

groups.name: Swing
groups.description: The group of dance styles that are traditionally danced to [Swing music] and trace their roots to the American nineteen twenties dance tradition centered in the [Savoy Ballroom](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savoy_Ballroom) are collectively known as *Swing* dances. These dances range from formal ballroom dances in both [American Rhythm] ([East Coast Swing]) and [International Latin] ([Jive]) syllabi to the more social variants of [Lindy Hop] and [West Coast Swing]. There are also many regional variants of swing including but definitely not limited to [Balboa] and [Carolina Shag].

groups.name: Performance
groups.description: Here at music4dance.net we're busily cataloging music with a specific interest in what dance styles 'work' with the music.  Since we come from a partner dancing background our system is set up primarily to work with traditional ballroom and partner social dancing like Swing, Salsa and Tango all of which are danced to music of a specific meter and tempo.  But with the interest in shows like *So You Think You Can Dance* and *Dancing With the Stars*, styles like Broadway, Contemporary, Jazz and even Ballet and Tap have started to show up in our database.  None of these style of dance operate under the same meter and tempo constraints that we are using, so we're creating initial place-holders for those styles and others that we'll roughly call 'performace' dances while we figure out how to generalize our website for such dance styles.

groups.name: Tango
groups.description: Tango refers to the dance styles that developed at the end of the nineteenth century in Buenos Aires and Montevideo and are danced to [Tango Music]. They include the traditional Tango Trinity of [Argentine Tango], [Milonga], and [Tango Vals].  Tango also refers to the substantially different dances styles of [American Smooth] and [International Standard] [Tango (Ballroom)] resulted from a migration to the northern hemisphere and shaping by the ballroom comunities.  We also include a much more recent evolution of the dance style [Neo Tango].

groups.name: Other
groups.description: This is the catch-all category for dances that we haven't yet grouped in a sensible way with other dances.  This list includes [Blues], [Country Two Step], [Motown], [Night Club Two Step] and [Polka].

groups.name: Foxtrot
groups.description: Foxtrot is the family of dances that developed in the nineteen tens and is danced to much the same music as the [Swing] dances. Both the [American Smooth] and the [International Standard] competition rounds contain [Slow Foxtrot]  and International style also contains a faster version of the *Foxtrot* called the [Quickstep]. Other dances in this family include the [Peabody] and the [Castle Foxtrot].

groups.name: Waltz
groups.description: Waltzes are dances that are danced to music in 3/4 time to the music of the same name.  They trace their roots to German and Austrian folk dance up through Viennese ballrooms and into modern ballroom competitions.  Both [American Smooth] and [International Standard] competition rounds have a [Slow Waltz] and a faster, [Viennese Waltz].
